Methods to check SQL Server database file type
To check the file type of a SQL Server database file, you can use the `HOST.FileRead` function in Axapta or Dynamics 365. Here's a code snippet that demonstrates how to do it:

// SQL Server supports MDF and LDF files.
// Making sure we're not trying to import a different file type (like a text file).

No Yes;

Yes = HOST.FileRead(@"C:\\Microsoft\\Data\\data.MDF");

if (Yes == null)
{
    Yes = false;
}
else
{
    Yes = true;
}

It's important to note that any other file will fail to open (return null) using `HOST.FileRead`.

Alternatively, you can use the `GETFILE` function to open a file and check if the first few bytes indicate an MDF or LDF file:

static void Job1(Args _args)
{
    str Line;
    struct FileHandle File;
    container FileInfo;

    File = GetFile("C:\\Microsoft\\Data\\Data.MDF");

    if (!File)
    {
        error("Could not open");
    }

    while(!FileIsEOF())
    {
        Line = FileReadLine();
    }

    FileClose(File);
}

However, this method is not recommended as it involves reading the entire file.

The `HOST.FileRead` method is the preferred approach for checking the file type of a SQL Server database file.
